{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619193"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16541"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16541"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.75,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76363"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9232"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61872"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7146"},{"type":"tags","id":"7152"},{"type":"tags","id":"10356"},{"type":"tags","id":"10359"},{"type":"tags","id":"10364"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21881"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76363"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum has a number of different afferent and efferent pathways that support its role in movement coordination. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cerebellothalamic tract?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Travels through the middle peduncle to ipsilateral thalamus then to ipsilateral motor neurons via corticospinal tract","Travels through the inferior peduncle to contralateral thalamus then to ipsilateral motor neurons via corticospinal tract","Travels through the superior peduncle to contralateral thalamus then to ipsilateral motor neurons via corticospinal tract","Travels through the superior peduncle to ipsilateral thalamus then to ipsilateral motor neurons via corticospinal tract","Receives information though the superior peduncle from the contralateral thalamus about the ipsilateral side of the body"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellothalamic tract\u003Cstrong\u003E travels through the superior peduncle to contralateral thalamus then to ipsilateral motor neurons via corticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E. This tract originates from the deep cerebellar nuclei and travels through the superior cerebellar peduncle to reach the opposite thalamus. The pathway then crosses back via corticospinal projections to influence the original side of the body, thereby exerting ipsilateral influence. This is referred to as \u0027double-crossing\u0027. The cerebellothalamic tract is an efferent pathway. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor these reasons the other options are incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cerebellothalamic tract carries output from the deep cerebellar nuclei through the superior cerebellar peduncle to the contralateral thalamus","The cerebellothalamic tract undergoes two midline crossings: first to the opposite thalamus, then via corticospinal projections back to the original side","The double-crossing arrangement of the cerebellothalamic tract explains why cerebellar lesions cause ipsilateral symptoms"],"references":["Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61872"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16541"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61872"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T09:27:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T09:27:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9232"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76363"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4904"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neuroanatomy","synonyms":[],"description":null